<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-100-317 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 032 615</DOCID><JOURNAL>Network World  July 29 1991 v8 n30 p11(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Users petition FCC to rethink fraud ruling. (ChartwaysTechnologies Inc., Mitsubishi International Corp. and PacificMutual Life Insurance Co. request U.S. Federal CommunicationsCommission to reopen case)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Taff, Anita.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The US Federal Communications Commission's (FCC's) ruling on tollfraud incites protests from several users who fear the agency'sdecision could impinge on efforts to establish national guidelinesfor ascertaining liability in telephone fraud.andP;  ChartwaysTechnologies Inc, Mitsubishi International Corp and Pacific MutualLife Insurance Co have requested that the FCC reopen the casebetween Chartway and ATandamp;T in which the FCC's Common Carrier Bureauheld the software services company liable for the total amount offraudulent calls made on ATandamp;T's network.andP;  Chartways officialscontend that ATandamp;T failed to warn them of the risks of toll fraudwhile ATandamp;T counters that tariff language makes explicit that userswill be responsible for paying all fraudulent charges placed overtheir networks.andP;  Chartways lost over $500,000 in the case andbelieves the legal implications warrant a re-examination of theruling.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Chartway Technologies (Cases)American Telephone and Telegraph Co. (Cases)Mitsubishi International Corp. (Management)Pacific Mutual Life Insurance Co. (Management).andO;Ticker:    T.andO;Topic:     United States. Federal Communications CommissionTelecommunications ServicesGovernment RegulationCourt CasesLegal IssuesTelephone CompaniesFraudLiability.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>